Here's the expanded calibration kernel design. Keeping the existing K1-K12 methodology (1 block, 1 warp, clock64, REPS=1024):

New kernels needed

K13a/K13b — IMAD throughput/latency (339 occurrences)
- K13a: 16 independent mad.lo.s32 %dst, %a, %b, %c (throughput)
- K13b: dependent chain mad.lo.s32 %0, %0, %1, %2 (latency)
- PTX mad.lo.s32 maps to SASS IMAD

K14a/K14b — IMAD.WIDE throughput/latency (67 occurrences of IMAD.WIDE)
- K14a: 16 independent mad.wide.s32 %dst, %a, %b, %c → produces 64-bit result
- K14b: dependent chain (feed low 32 bits back)
- Important: IMAD.WIDE may use different functional unit than IMAD

K15a/K15b — LOP3 throughput/latency (77 occurrences)
- K15a: 16 independent lop3.b32 %dst, %a, %b, %c, 0xE8 (throughput)
- K15b: dependent chain (latency)

K16a/K16b — SHF throughput/latency (64 occurrences)
- K16a: 16 independent shf.r.clamp.b32 %dst, %a, %b, %c (throughput)
- K16b: dependent chain (latency)
- PTX shf maps to SASS SHF

K17a/K17b — MOV throughput/latency (35 occurrences)
- K17a: 16 independent mov.b32 %dst, %src with different src/dst (throughput)
- K17b: dependent chain mov.b32 %0, %0 — but this may be eliminated by compiler. Instead: mov.b32 → add.s32 %0, %0, 0 → mov.b32 chain to
prevent elimination
- Actually simpler: mov.b32 %0, %1; mov.b32 %1, %0 alternating

K18a/K18b — LEA throughput/latency (25 occurrences)
- K18a: independent mad.lo.s32 %dst, %a, 1, %b (which compiles to LEA)
- Actually LEA is %dst = %a * scale + %b + offset. In PTX there's no direct LEA; it comes from address computation. Use inline asm.

K19a/K19b — VIADD throughput/latency (75 occurrences)
- VIADD is a video instruction. PTX: vadd.s32.s32.s32. In inline asm: "vadd.s32.s32.s32 %0, %1, %2, %3;"

K20a/K20b — R2UR throughput/latency (408 occurrences — most frequent!)
- "r2ur.result UR4, R5;" — cross-domain register transfer
- PTX doesn't have a direct equivalent. Needs SASS-level inline or a trick.
- Actually in the patch embed kernel it appears as R2UR and R2UR.BROADCAST. The PTX for this is just referencing uniform registers from scalar
context, or using mov from R to UR space.
- Can use: asm volatile("mov.u32 %%ur0, %0;" :: "r"(val)); — maps to R2UR

K21a/K21b — ISETP throughput/latency (47 occurrences)
- K21a: independent setp.ne.s32 %p, %a, %b (throughput)
- K21b: dependent — predicate feeds next selp which feeds next setp

K22 — LDS latency (70 occurrences)
- Pointer chase in shared memory: ld.shared.b32 %idx, [smem + %idx*4]
- Pre-fill smem with self-referencing indices (like K12 for global)

K23 — STG throughput (65 occurrences)
- Independent st.global.b64 to different addresses
- Throughput matters, not latency (fire-and-forget like STS?)

K24a/K24b — S2R throughput/latency (10 occurrences)
- K24a: independent mov.u32 %dst, %tid.x repeated
- K24b: dependent chain is hard (S2R reads special regs, doesn't write them). Just throughput.

K25a/K25b — UMOV throughput/latency (51 occurrences, uniform pipe)
- asm volatile("mov.u32 %%ur4, %0;" :: "r"(val)) followed by uniform ops

K26a/K26b — UIADD3 throughput/latency (39 occurrences, uniform pipe)
- Need to verify if uniform IADD3 has same latency as scalar IADD3 (K7b measured 2 cycles)

That's 14 new kernel pairs (K13-K26) plus K22, K23, K24 standalone = roughly 17 new kernels. Combined with existing K1-K12, total of ~29
kernels.

The hard ones to write are:
- R2UR (K20) — cross-domain, needs careful asm
- VIADD (K19) — video instruction, unusual encoding
- LEA (K18) — compiler artifact, may need inline asm tricks
- UIADD3/UMOV/USHF (K25-K27) — uniform pipeline, UR registers

